Two Voices, Ng explores how English and Cantonese respectively reinforce and undermine the practice of legal formalism. This first-ever ethnographic study of Hong Kong's unique legal system in the midst of social and political transition, this book provides important insights into the social nature of language and the work of institutions. Ng contends that the dilemma of legal bilingualism in Hong Kong is emblematic of the inherent tensions of postcolonial Hong Kong. Through the legal dramas presented in the book, readers will get a fresh look at the former British colony that is now searching for its identity within a powerful China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCantonese dialectsxSocial aspectsxChinaxHong Kong. 0aCantonese dialectsxSocial aspectszChinazHong Kong. 0aConduct of court proceedingsxLanguagexChinaxHong Kong. 0aConduct of court proceedingszChinazHong KongxLanguage. 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspectsxChinaxHong Kong. 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspectszChinazHong Kong. 0aLawxLanguagexChinaxHong Kong. 0aLawzChinazHong KongxLanguage. 7aLAW / Comparative.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772358zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772358.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles